gg_tsresiduals(tlb_fit %>% select(arima_110)) +
  labs(title = "Residuals: TLB ARIMA(1,1,0)")

gg_tsresiduals(tlb_fit %>% select(arima_111)) +
  labs(title = "Residuals: TLB ARIMA(1,1,1)")

gg_tsresiduals(tfr_fit %>% select(arima_auto)) +
  labs(title = "Residuals: TFR ARIMA(0,2,1)")

gg_tsresiduals(tfr_fit %>% select(arima_120)) +
  labs(title = "Residuals: TFR ARIMA(1,2,0)")

gg_tsresiduals(tfr_fit %>% select(arima_121)) +
  labs(title = "Residuals: TFR ARIMA(1,2,1)")


# For the TLB models, the residual series appear broadly random, with the main
# exception being a pronounced spike around 1988. A similar feature is visible in
# the TFR residuals, although it is less pronounced. This is consistent with the
# original time series plots, where the movement around 1988 is relatively larger
# for TLB than for TFR.

# The residual ACFs show only minor differences across the candidate models within
# each series. However, when comparing across series, the TFR models tend to show
# slightly larger autocorrelations on average than the TLB models, suggesting that
# more residual dependence remains in the TFR fits.

# The residual distributions do not appear severely skewed for any of the models.

# Inspection of residual plots alone did not much insights in regards to distinguishing,
# better or worse fits based on parameter choice for the ARIMA models. So I decided
# to runs some L Jung box tests at lag 10 as well as looking at the results from
# glance to get a better insight.


augment(tlb_fit %>% select(arima_auto)) %>%
  features(.resid, ljung_box, lag = 10, dof = 0) #p=.702

augment(tlb_fit %>% select(arima_110)) %>%
  features(.resid, ljung_box, lag = 10, dof = 1) #p=.663

augment(tlb_fit %>% select(arima_111)) %>%
  features(.resid, ljung_box, lag = 10, dof = 2) #p=.518

augment(tfr_fit %>% select(arima_auto)) %>%
  features(.resid, ljung_box, lag = 10, dof = 1) #p=.236

augment(tfr_fit %>% select(arima_120)) %>%
  features(.resid, ljung_box, lag = 10, dof = 1) #p=.0959

augment(tfr_fit %>% select(arima_121)) %>%
  features(.resid, ljung_box, lag = 10, dof = 2) #p=.320

glance(tlb_fit)
glance(tfr_fit)

# Inspection of the residual plots alone did not provide much basis for clearly
# distinguishing between the ARIMA models. To compare the candidate models more
# formally, Ljung–Box tests were applied at lag 10 and the model summaries from
# glance() were also examined.

# For the TLB models, all Ljung–Box p-values were comfortably above 0.05,
# suggesting no strong evidence of remaining residual autocorrelation at lag 10.
# Among these, ARIMA(0,1,0) performed best according to AIC, AICc, and BIC,
# although the differences relative to ARIMA(1,1,0) were fairly small.
# This suggests that the simpler ARIMA(0,1,0) model is a reasonable candidate
# for TLB.

# For the TFR models, all Ljung–Box p-values also remained above 0.05, although
# ARIMA(1,2,0) produced the weakest result, with a p-value closer to the rejection
# threshold. Comparing the information criteria, ARIMA(0,2,1) had the lowest
# AIC, AICc, and BIC, with ARIMA(1,2,1) close behind. This suggests that
# ARIMA(0,2,1) is the strongest candidate among the models considered for TFR,
# while ARIMA(1,2,1) may also remain a plausible alternative.





